entries.body:
A **Client-Side Path Traversal (CSPT)** finder: a hook on `fetch`/`XHR` in the browser that logs all outgoing requests and checks whether controllable input can smuggle in `../` and change the fetch path to a foreign endpoint. The CSPT2CSRF class (Doyensec, 2024-2025) is one of the hot ones: roughly a fifth of 2025's web bugs.

> You paste it as a snippet into the DevTools Console on the target page. Then you click around the app - the hook shows which fetches build a URL from user input. If `../../` lands in the path and the server swallows it, that is CSPT, which is often escalated to CSRF against a sensitive endpoint.

deps: none (DevTools console). placeholders: `{{MARKER}}` (a marker string from your input, e.g. a file name/id).

```javascript
// cspt_finder.js - ARS3NAL (GPL-3.0). Paste in DevTools console. AUTHORIZED only.
(() => {
  const MARKER = "ars3nal";            // put your own controllable input here
  const TRAVERSAL = /\.\.(\/|%2f|\\)/i;
  const log = (tag, url, extra="") =>
    console.log(`%c[CSPT ${tag}]`, "color:#e63", url, extra);

  // 1) hook fetch
  const _fetch = window.fetch;
  window.fetch = function (input, init) {
    const url = (typeof input === "string") ? input : (input && input.url) || "";
    if (url.includes(MARKER)) log("fetch+marker", url);
    if (TRAVERSAL.test(url)) log("fetch TRAVERSAL", url, "<-- path escapes!");
    // heuristic: input lands in a path segment, not in the query
    try {
      const u = new URL(url, location.origin);
      if (u.pathname.includes(MARKER)) log("marker in PATH (CSPT-prone)", u.pathname);
    } catch (e) {}
    return _fetch.apply(this, arguments);
  };

  // 2) hook XHR
  const _open = XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open;
  XMLHttpRequest.prototype.open = function (method, url) {
    if (String(url).includes(MARKER)) log("xhr+marker", url);
    if (TRAVERSAL.test(String(url))) log("xhr TRAVERSAL", url, "<-- path escapes!");
    return _open.apply(this, arguments);
  };

  console.log("%c[ARS3NAL CSPT hook armed]", "color:#3c3",
    `marker=${MARKER}. Now click around the app and watch for [CSPT ...].`);
})();
```

Run:
```text
1. Open the target, type the MARKER string into an input (file name/id/category).
2. Paste the snippet into the DevTools Console and press Enter.
3. Click around the app. A [CSPT ...] log -> the input landed in the fetch PATH.
4. Put ../../api/admin instead of MARKER -> if the server processed it, that is CSPT (-> CSRF).
```
